          "body": "Zedekiah's first approach to Jeremiah is revealing precisely for what it asks and what it avoids. He sends two delegates — a royal official and a priest — with the request: 'Please pray to the LORD our God on our behalf' (37:3). He does not ask Jeremiah to speak the word of the LORD. He does not ask for direction or counsel. He asks the prophet to pray — to intercede, to manage God's response to a political crisis. This is instrumental religion: using the prophet as a conduit to divine assistance without accepting the prophet's authority over one's own decisions. The LORD's response is not prayer-shaped comfort but a word of inescapable judgment: Pharaoh's army will return to Egypt, the Chaldeans will return to Jerusalem, and they will 'capture it and burn it with fire' (37:8). The LORD then drives the oracle to its rhetorical extreme in verse 10 — even if only wounded Babylonian soldiers remained, they would rise from their tents and burn the city. The hyperbole is deliberate: it forecloses every military scenario in which obedience might seem unnecessary. There is no version of events in which this word does not stand."
