          "body": "Zedekiah's response is the chapter's final irony: he transfers Jeremiah to the court of the guardhouse and gives him daily bread from the bakers' street 'until all the bread in the city was gone' (37:21). It is mercy — but it is not obedience. The king who has just heard 'You will be given into the hand of the king of Babylon' takes no action on the word, makes no change of political direction, and initiates no national repentance. He simply improves the prophet's living conditions. The bread continues until it runs out — a detail the narrator inserts to remind the reader that the city is under siege, that famine is coming, and that every day of bread is borrowed time. Yet within the chapter's theology, God's provision of daily bread for Jeremiah even within confinement is significant: the prophet is sustained through the crisis he has been predicting. He will survive to see the word fulfilled (39:11-14). The chapter ends not with resolution but with patient continuation — Jeremiah in the guardhouse court, the city running out of bread, the word of the LORD still standing."
